|-
| &lt;big&gt;{{my|ဟ}}&lt;/big&gt;&lt;br/&gt;h ({{IPA|/haˀ/}}) || &lt;big&gt;{{my|ဠ}}&lt;/big&gt;&lt;br/&gt;ḷ ({{IPA|/laˀ/}}) || &lt;big&gt;{{my|ၜ}}&lt;/big&gt;&lt;br/&gt;b ({{IPA|/ɓaˀ/~[baˀ]}}) || &lt;big&gt;{{my|အ}}&lt;/big&gt;&lt;br/&gt;a ({{IPA|/ʔaˀ/}}) ||style=&quot;background-color:#ccc&quot;| &lt;big&gt;{{my|ၝ}}&lt;/big&gt;&lt;br/&gt;mb ({{IPA|/ɓɛ̤ˀ/~[bɛ̤ˀ]}})
|}

In the Mon script, consonants belong to one of two registers: clear and breathy, each of which has different inherent vowels and pronunciations for the same set of diacritics. For instance, {{my|က}}, which belongs to the clear register, is pronounced {{IPA|/kaˀ/}}, while {{my|ဂ}} is pronounced {{IPA|/kɛ̤ˀ/}}, to accommodate the vowel complexity of the Mon phonology.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite book |title=Concise encyclopedia of languages of the world |chapter=Mon |year=2009 |publisher=Elsevier |location= |isbn=978-0-08-087774-7 |pages=719–20 }}&lt;/ref&gt; The addition of diacritics makes this obvious. Whereas in Burmese spellings with the same diacritics are rhyming, in Mon this depends on the consonant's inherent register. A few examples are listed below:
* {{my|က}} + {{my|ဳ}} → {{my|ကဳ}}, pronounced {{IPA|/kɔe/}}
* {{my|ဂ}} + {{my|ဳ}} → {{my|ဂဳ}}, pronounced {{IPA|/ki̤/}}
* {{my|က}} + {{my|ူ}} → {{my|ကူ}}, pronounced {{IPA|/kao/}}
* {{my|ဂ}} + {{my|ူ}} → {{my|ဂူ}}, pronounced {{IPA|/kṳ/}}

The Mon language has 8 medials, as follows: {{my|္ၚ}} ({{IPA|/-ŋ-/}}), {{my|ၞ}} ({{IPA|/-n-/}}), {{my|ၟ}} ({{IPA|/-m-/}}), {{my|ျ}} ({{IPA|/-j-/}}), {{my|ြ}} ({{IPA|/-r-/}}), {{my|ၠ}} ({{IPA|/-l-/}}), {{my|ွ}} ({{IPA|/-w-/}}), and {{my|ှ}} ({{IPA|/-hn-/}}).

Consonantal finals are indicated with a [[virama]] ({{my|်}}), as in Burmese: however, instead of being pronounced as glottal stops as in Burmese, final consonants usually keep their respective pronunciations. Furthermore, consonant stacking is possible in Mon spellings, particularly for [[Pali]] and [[Sanskrit]]-derived vocabulary.

===Vowels===
Mon uses the same diacritics and diacritic combinations as in Burmese to represent vowels, with the addition of a few diacritics unique to the Mon script, including {{my|ဴ}} ({{IPA|/ɛ̀a/}}), and {{my|ဳ}} ({{IPA|/i/}}), since the diacritic {{my|ိ}} represents {{IPA|/ìˀ/}}.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/31170845/Mon-Vowels-Characters |title=Mon Vowels Characters |author=Dho-ong Jhaan |date=2010-05-10 |work= |publisher= |accessdate=12 September 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; Also, {{my|ဨ}} ({{IPA|/e/}}) is used instead of {{my|ဧ}}, as in Burmese.

